◆ dlp_ptohdate()

time_t dlp_ptohdate ( const unsigned char * data)
772{
773 struct tm t;
774
775 /* Seems like year comes back as all zeros if the date is "empty"
776 (but other fields can vary). And mktime() chokes on 1900 B.C.
777 (result of 0 minus 1900), returning -1, which the higher level
778 code can't deal with (passes it straight on to utime(), which
779 simply leaves the file's timestamp "as-is").
780
781 So, since year 0 appears to mean "no date", we'll return an odd
782 number that works out to precisely one day before the start of
783 the Palm's clock (thus little chance of being run into by any
784 Palm-based time stamp). */
785
786 if (data[0] == 0 && data[1] == 0) {
787
788 /* This original calculation was wrong, and reported one day
789 earlier than it was supposed to report. You can verify
790 this with the following:
791
792 perl -e '$date=localtime(0x83D8FE00); print $date,"\n"'
793
794 return (time_t) 0x83D8FE00; // Wed Dec 30 16:00:00 1903 GMT
795
796 Here are others, depending on what your system requirements are:
797
798 return (time_t) 0x83D96E80; // Thu Dec 31 00:00:00 1903 GMT
799 return (time_t) 0x00007080; // Thu Jan 1 00:00:00 1970 GMT
800
801 Palm's own Conduit Development Kit references using 1/1/1904,
802 so that's what we'll use here until something else breaks
803 it.
804 */
805
806 return (time_t) 0x83DAC000; /* Fri Jan 1 00:00:00 1904 GMT */
807 }
808
809 memset(&t, 0, sizeof(t));
810 t.tm_sec = (int) data[6];
811 t.tm_min = (int) data[5];
812 t.tm_hour = (int) data[4];
813 t.tm_mday = (int) data[3];
814 t.tm_mon = (int) data[2] - 1;
815 t.tm_year = (((int)data[0] << 8) | (int)data[1]) - 1900;
816 t.tm_isdst = -1;
817
818 return mktime(&t);
819}
